<subsection xml:id="subsec-velocity-time-graph">
    <title>Velocity Time Graph</title>
    <activity>
        <p>
            <m>\textbf{Work in groups}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        A train moving at <m>40 \text{ m/s}</m> along a North-South railway track passes through a station R at <m>5:30 \textbf{ PM}</m>. The train is decelerating at <m>4 \textbf{ m/s²}</m> northward.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Find the velocity of the train:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>3 \textbf{ seconds}</m>  after <m>5:30 \textbf{ PM}</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>6 \textbf{ seconds}</m>  after <m>5:30 \textbf{ PM}</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <m>2 \textbf{ seconds}</m>  after <m>5:30 \textbf{ PM}</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Determine the average velocity of the train:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    In the first <m>5 \textbf{ seconds}</m>  after <m>5:30 \textbf{ PM}</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    In the first <m>10 \textbf{ seconds}</m>  after <m>5:30 \textbf{ PM}</m>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Draw a velocity-time graph, find the distance of the train from R at <m>12</m> seconds past <m>5:30 \textbf{ PM}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
        A velocity-time graph is a graph that shows how an object's velocity (speed with direction) changes over time.
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key Features of a Velocity-Time Graph:}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    X-Axis (Horizontal Axis): Represents time (e.g., seconds, minutes, hours).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Y-Axis (Vertical Axis): Represents velocity (e.g., m/s, km/h).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Slope of the Graph: Represents acceleration (how fast velocity is changing).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Area Under the Graph: Represents displacement (total distance covered).
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Types of Velocity-Time Graphs:}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Horizontal Line:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The object is moving at a constant velocity (zero acceleration).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Upward Sloping Line:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The object is accelerating (velocity is increasing).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Downward Sloping Line:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The object is decelerating (velocity is decreasing).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Line at Zero Velocity:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The object not moving.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Acceleration}</m> is the rate of change of velocity of an object over time. It occurs when an object speeds up, slows down, or changes direction.
    </p>
    
    <p>
        <md>
            <mrow>\textbf{Acceleration} = \amp \frac{\textbf{Change in velocity}}{\textbf{Corresponding change in time}}</mrow>
            <mrow>\textbf{a} = \amp \frac{\textbf{Δv}}{\textbf{Δt}}</mrow>
            <mrow>\textbf{a} = \amp \frac{\textbf{v - u}}{\textbf{t}}</mrow>
        </md>
    </p>
    <p>
        Where;
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{a}</m> = Acceleration which is measured in <m>\textbf{m/s²}</m>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Δv}</m> = <m>\textbf{v - u}</m> = change in velocity which is measured in metres per second <m>\textbf{m/s}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{v}</m> is the final velocity and <m>\textbf{u}</m> is the initial velocity.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Δt}</m> = <m>\textbf{t}</m> = time taken which is measured in seconds(s)
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Deceleration}</m> is negative acceleration, meaning the object is slowing down. It happens when the velocity decreases over time.
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    In a velocity-time graph, deceleration appears as a downward-sloping line.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The velocity-time graph helps determine an object's acceleration, displacement (area under the graph), and motion type (uniform or non-uniform). 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Given the table below
            </p>
            <table>
                <title></title>
                <tabular left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
                    <row halign="center" header="yes">
                        <cell>Time</cell>
                        <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>6</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>7</m></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row halign="center" header="yes">
                        <cell>Velocity (m/s)</cell>
                        <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>10</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>20</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>30</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>40</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>40</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>30</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>10</m></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>
            <p>
                Draw the velocity-time graph to represent the data.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                This is a velocity-time graph that shows Acceleration, Constant Speed, and Deceleration.
            </p>
            <image width="60%">
                <latex-image label = "Velocity1">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Draw fine grid (10x smaller squares)
                        \draw[gray!30, very thin, step=0.1] (0,0) grid (9,8);
                        % Draw main grid (original)
                        \draw[gray!70, thin, step=1] (0,0) grid (9,8);
                        
                        % Axes
                        \draw[thick,->] (0,0) -- (9,0);
                        \draw[thick,->] (0,0) -- (0,8);
                        \node[above, rotate=90] at (-0.8,3.5) {\textbf {Velocity (m/s)}};
                        \node[below] at (4.5,-0.4) {\textbf{Time (seconds)}};
                        
                        % Y-axis labels
                        \foreach \y in {10,20,30,40,50,60,70}
                            \draw (-0.2,\y/10) -- (0.2,\y/10) node[left=7pt] {\y};
                        
                        % X-axis labels - Starting from 0
                        \foreach \x in {1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8}
                            \draw (\x,-0.2) -- (\x,0.2) node[below=7pt] {\x};
                        
                        % Graph Title
                        \node[above] at (4,8) {\textbf{Velocity-Time Graph}};
                        
                        % Journey segments - Starting from time 0
                        \draw[thick,black] (0,0) -- (1,1); % 0 to 1s (0 to 10m/s)
                        \draw[thick,black] (1,1) -- (2,2); % 1 to 2s (10 to 20m/s)
                        \draw[thick,black] (2,2) -- (3,3); % 2 to 3s (20 to 30m/s)
                        \draw[thick,black] (3,3) -- (4,4); % 3 to 4s (30 to 40m/s)
                        \draw[thick,black] (4,4) -- (5,4); % 4 to 5s (constant at 40m/s)
                        \draw[thick,black] (5,4) -- (6,3); % 5 to 6s (40 to 30m/s)
                        \draw[thick,black] (6,3) -- (7,1); % 6 to 7s (30 to 10m/s)
                        
                        % Points at each time
                        \fill (1,1) circle (2pt);
                        \fill (2,2) circle (2pt);
                        \fill (3,3) circle (2pt);
                        \fill (4,4) circle (2pt);
                        \fill (5,4) circle (2pt);
                        \fill (6,3) circle (2pt);
                        \fill (7,1) circle (2pt);
                        
                        % Dashed black lines from each point to axes
                        \draw[black, dashed] (1,1) -- (0,1);
                        \draw[black, dashed] (1,1) -- (1,0);
                        \draw[black, dashed] (2,2) -- (0,2);
                        \draw[black, dashed] (2,2) -- (2,0);
                        \draw[black, dashed] (3,3) -- (0,3);
                        \draw[black, dashed] (3,3) -- (3,0);
                        \draw[black, dashed] (4,4) -- (0,4);
                        \draw[black, dashed] (4,4) -- (4,0);
                        \draw[black, dashed] (5,4) -- (0,4);
                        \draw[black, dashed] (5,4) -- (5,0);
                        \draw[black, dashed] (6,3) -- (0,3);
                        \draw[black, dashed] (6,3) -- (6,0);
                        \draw[black, dashed] (7,1) -- (0,1);
                        \draw[black, dashed] (7,1) -- (7,0);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A car starts from rest and accelerates to a velocity of <m>40 \textbf{ m/s}</m> in <m>10 \textbf{ seconds}</m> . It then maintains this velocity for <m>15 \textbf{ seconds}</m> before decelerating to rest, with the total time of motion being <m>45 \textbf{ seconds}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Draw the velocity-time graph to represent its motion.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the total distance covered.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Determine the average velocity.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculate the acceleration and deceleration.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The velocity-time graph;
                        </p>
                        <image width="60%">
                            <latex-image label = "Velocity2">
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    % Draw fine grid (10x smaller squares)
                                    \draw[gray!30, very thin, step=0.1] (0,0) grid (10,5);
                                    
                                    % Draw main grid
                                    \draw[gray!70, thin, step=1] (0,0) grid (10,5);
                                    
                                    % Axes
                                    \draw[thick,->] (0,0) -- (10,0);
                                    \draw[thick,->] (0,0) -- (0,5);
                                    \node[above, rotate=90] at (-0.8,2) {\textbf {Velocity (m/s)}};
                                    \node[below] at (4.5,-0.4) {\textbf{Time (seconds)}};
                                    
                                    % Y-axis labels (velocity)
                                    \foreach \y in {10,20,30,40}
                                        \draw (-0.2,\y/10) -- (0.2,\y/10) node[left=7pt] {\y};
                                    
                                    % X-axis labels (time)
                                    \foreach \x in {10,20,30,40,45}
                                        \draw (\x/5,-0.2) -- (\x/5,0.2) node[below=7pt] {\x};
                                    
                                    % Graph Title
                                    \node[above] at (4.5,5) {\textbf{Velocity-Time Graph}};
                                    
                                    % Velocity-time graph
                                    \draw[thick,black] (0,0) -- (2,4);  % Acceleration phase (0 to 10s, 0 to 40 m/s)
                                    \draw[thick,black] (2,4) -- (5,4);  % Constant velocity (10s to 25s, 40 m/s)
                                    \draw[thick,black] (5,4) -- (9,0);  % Deceleration phase (25s to 45s, 40 to 0 m/s)
                                    
                                    % Points at key moments
                                    \fill (2,4) circle (2pt);
                                    \fill (5,4) circle (2pt);
                                    \fill (9,0) circle (2pt);
                                    
                                    % Dashed lines for reference
                                    \draw[black, dashed] (2,4) -- (0,4);
                                    \draw[black, dashed] (5,4) -- (0,4);
                                    \draw[black, dashed] (9,0) -- (0,0);
                                    \draw[black, dashed] (2,4) -- (2,0);
                                    \draw[black, dashed] (5,4) -- (5,0);
                                    \draw[black, dashed] (9,0) -- (9,0);
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The total distance is the area under the velocity-time graph, which consists of a trapezium.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Distance during acceleration (triangle).
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        <md>
                                            <mrow>\textbf{Area} = \amp \frac{1}{2}\times \textbf{ base}\times \textbf{ height}</mrow>
                                            <mrow> \amp \frac{1}{2} \times 10 \times 40</mrow>
                                            <mrow>= \amp 200\textbf{ m}</mrow>
                                        </md>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Distance during constant velocity (rectangle)
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                    <md>
                                        <mrow>\textbf{Area} = \textbf{base} \times \textbf{ height}\amp </mrow>
                                        <mrow> \amp 15 \times 40</mrow>
                                        <mrow>=  \amp 600\textbf{ m}</mrow>
                                    </md>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Distance during deceleration (triangle)
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        <md>
                                            <mrow>\textbf{Area} = \amp \frac{1}{2}\times \textbf{ base}\times \textbf{ height}</mrow>
                                            <mrow> \amp 20 \times 40</mrow>
                                            <mrow>=  \amp 400\textbf{ m}</mrow>
                                        </md>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Total distance:
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        <m>200+600+400</m> = <m>1200\textbf{ m}</m>
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Therefore, the total distance is <m>1200\textbf{ m}</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Average Velocity
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\textbf{Average velocity} = \amp \frac{\textbf{Total distance}}{\textbf{ Total time}}</mrow>
                                <mrow> =  \amp \frac{1200}{45}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = 26.67\textbf{ m/s}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Therefore, the average velocity is <m>26.67\textbf{ m/s}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Acceleration and Deceleration
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Using the equation:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\textbf{a} = \amp \frac{\textbf{v - u}}{\textbf{t}}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Where;
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\textbf{v}</m> = is the final velocity (<m>40 \textbf{ m/s}</m>, from the graph)
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\textbf{u}</m> = is the initial velocity (<m>0 \textbf{ m/s}</m>)
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\textbf{t}</m> = is the time taken during acceleration (<m>10 \textbf{ seconds}</m>).
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \amp \frac{40 - 0}{10}</mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp 4\textbf{ m/s²}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Therefore, acceleration is <m>4\textbf{ m/s²}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Under deceleration;
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\textbf{v}</m> is the final velocity (<m>0 \textbf{ m/s}</m>, since the car comes to rest),
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\textbf{u}</m> is the initial velocity (<m>40 \textbf{ m/s}</m>, from the graph)
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\textbf{t}</m> is the time taken during deceleration (<m>10 \textbf{ seconds}</m>).
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \amp \frac{0 - 40}{10}</mrow>
                                <mrow>= \amp -4\textbf{ m/s²}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Therefore, the object is decelerating at  <m> 4\textbf{ m/s²}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            
        </solution>
    </example>
